Model¶

Regression¶

In [51]:
import statsmodels.api as sm
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
lr_model = sm.OLS(y_train, sm.add_constant(X_train))
lr_result = lr_model.fit()
y_pred = lr_result.predict(sm.add_constant(X_test))
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
n = X_train.shape[0]
p = X_train.shape[1]
adj_r2 = 1 - (1 - r2) * ((n - 1) / (n - p - 1))
print(lr_result.summary())
print("R-squared:", r2)
print("Adjusted R-squared:", adj_r2)
print("p-value of the model:", lr_result.f_pvalue)

ARIMA¶

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

In [56]:
energy_consumption_ts = filtered_df['Energy Consumption']

def check_stationarity(data):
    from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller
    result = adfuller(data)
    return result[1] < 0.05

def make_stationary(data):
    stationary_data = data.diff().dropna()  
    return stationary_data

if not check_stationarity(energy_consumption_ts):
    stationary_energy_consumption_ts = make_stationary(energy_consumption_ts)
    print("Energy Consumption time series is now stationary.")
else:
    print("Energy Consumption time series is already stationary.")

Energy Consumption time series is now stationary.
In [57]:
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA
p = 1  
d = 1 
q = 2 
arima_model = ARIMA(stationary_energy_consumption_ts, order=(p, d, q))
arima_result = arima_model.fit()
print(arima_result.summary())
